WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.948 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:01.948 --> 00:00:03.896 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:03.896 --> 00:00:10.720 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:10.720 --> 00:00:11.950 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: OK.

00:00:11.950 --> 00:00:12.450 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:00:12.450 --> 00:00:17.930 align:middle line:84%
So last lecture, we
talked about the property

00:00:17.930 --> 00:00:24.230 align:middle line:84%
of this propagator,
which is defined

00:00:24.230 --> 00:00:31.880 align:middle line:84%
to be x, x prime which is
also the same as phi x,

00:00:31.880 --> 00:00:34.910 align:middle line:90%
phi x prime here.

00:00:34.910 --> 00:00:36.140 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:00:36.140 --> 00:00:40.010 align:middle line:90%
So this object, we discussed.

00:00:40.010 --> 00:00:42.630 align:middle line:84%
So conceptually, it
can be considered--

00:00:42.630 --> 00:00:45.330 align:middle line:90%
so you have two interpretations.

00:00:45.330 --> 00:00:48.660 align:middle line:90%
So one is from here.

00:00:48.660 --> 00:00:57.840 align:middle line:84%
So this roughly can be
heuristically interpreted

00:00:57.840 --> 00:01:16.380 align:middle line:84%
as the transition amplitude for
a particle from x to x prime.

00:01:16.380 --> 00:01:20.960 align:middle line:84%
OK, so heuristically,
you can think of it, say,

00:01:20.960 --> 00:01:22.460 align:middle line:90%
if you have a point--

00:01:22.460 --> 00:01:26.090 align:middle line:84%
say, if you have a
space-time point, x

00:01:26.090 --> 00:01:28.550 align:middle line:90%
prime has another points x.

00:01:28.550 --> 00:01:32.510 align:middle line:84%
And then you ask, what's
the transition amplitude

00:01:32.510 --> 00:01:34.894 align:middle line:90%
from x prime to x?

00:01:34.894 --> 00:01:40.700 align:middle line:84%
OK, so one way to interpret
this object is that.

00:01:40.700 --> 00:01:45.260 align:middle line:84%
And as I emphasize, this
is only heuristically,

00:01:45.260 --> 00:01:48.080 align:middle line:84%
because this does
not really describe

00:01:48.080 --> 00:01:49.880 align:middle line:90%
a generally localized state.

00:01:49.880 --> 00:01:55.770 align:middle line:84%
It's only a approximately
localized state, OK?

00:01:55.770 --> 00:02:01.770 align:middle line:84%
And similarly, the
second interpretation

00:02:01.770 --> 00:02:03.315 align:middle line:90%
is the correlation function.

00:02:03.315 --> 00:02:10.130 align:middle line:90%


00:02:10.130 --> 00:02:25.270 align:middle line:84%
It describes correlations
of phi between, say, x.

00:02:25.270 --> 00:02:30.700 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, just correlations,
square correlations

00:02:30.700 --> 00:02:39.190 align:middle line:84%
between the value of phi at
x prime and the value of phi

00:02:39.190 --> 00:02:39.755 align:middle line:90%
at x.

00:02:39.755 --> 00:02:48.160 align:middle line:84%
OK, so this is the
interpretation most convenient,

00:02:48.160 --> 00:02:50.140 align:middle line:84%
for example, from condensed
matter perspective

00:02:50.140 --> 00:02:52.900 align:middle line:84%
if your phi, say,
describes average spins.

00:02:52.900 --> 00:02:53.620 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:02:53.620 --> 00:03:05.500 align:middle line:84%
So similarly, the
G minus, which is

00:03:05.500 --> 00:03:15.930 align:middle line:84%
defined to be in
the opposite order,

00:03:15.930 --> 00:03:20.040 align:middle line:90%
also have two interpretations.

00:03:20.040 --> 00:03:26.130 align:middle line:84%
So this is like a transition
from x to x prime.

00:03:26.130 --> 00:03:31.170 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, so if I draw x and
if I still draw x that way,

00:03:31.170 --> 00:03:33.470 align:middle line:84%
so it's like a transition
amplitude like this,

00:03:33.470 --> 00:03:35.610 align:middle line:90%
from x to x prime.

00:03:35.610 --> 00:03:37.350 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:03:37.350 --> 00:03:42.690 align:middle line:84%
So you can similarly interpret
the other using this language,

00:03:42.690 --> 00:03:57.530 align:middle line:84%
for example, this Feynman,
which is theta G plus x, x prime

00:03:57.530 --> 00:04:04.240 align:middle line:90%
plus x minus.

00:04:04.240 --> 00:04:10.720 align:middle line:84%
And then this means that when
t is greater than t prime,

00:04:10.720 --> 00:04:13.660 align:middle line:84%
say, for now, let's
take this to be

00:04:13.660 --> 00:04:15.700 align:middle line:90%
the direction of time going up.

00:04:15.700 --> 00:04:21.339 align:middle line:84%
And now if the x has a
later time than x prime,

00:04:21.339 --> 00:04:25.730 align:middle line:84%
and then describe the
transition from x prime to x.

00:04:25.730 --> 00:04:26.230 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:04:26.230 --> 00:04:34.930 align:middle line:84%
But if the x prime has a larger
time, and x has a smaller time,

00:04:34.930 --> 00:04:39.410 align:middle line:84%
and then describe the opposite
direction from x to x prime.

00:04:39.410 --> 00:04:42.340 align:middle line:84%
But in both cases, you always
go from the smaller time

00:04:42.340 --> 00:04:43.090 align:middle line:90%
to bigger time.

00:04:43.090 --> 00:04:44.170 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:04:44.170 --> 00:04:47.170 align:middle line:84%
And so we often
call this, also GF,

00:04:47.170 --> 00:04:49.670 align:middle line:84%
the time-ordered
correlation function.

00:04:49.670 --> 00:04:52.270 align:middle line:90%
So the GF is also called--

00:04:52.270 --> 00:04:54.670 align:middle line:84%
so it's called the
Feynman-Green functions.

00:04:54.670 --> 00:05:01.480 align:middle line:84%
It's also called the
time-ordered correlation

00:05:01.480 --> 00:05:01.980 align:middle line:90%
function.

00:05:01.980 --> 00:05:10.850 align:middle line:90%


00:05:10.850 --> 00:05:14.430 align:middle line:84%
And then we wrote
down the expression.

00:05:14.430 --> 00:05:18.410 align:middle line:84%
So we calculate the expression
explicitly for G plus.

00:05:18.410 --> 00:05:23.690 align:middle line:84%
And we also almost finished
the expression for--

00:05:23.690 --> 00:05:26.780 align:middle line:84%
yeah, similarly, you can
do retarded et cetera.

00:05:26.780 --> 00:05:30.980 align:middle line:84%
And also, so any
questions on this?

00:05:30.980 --> 00:05:32.060 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:05:32.060 --> 00:05:33.950 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So on
the set, we showed

00:05:33.950 --> 00:05:37.910 align:middle line:84%
that for the complex scalar
field, phi x phi x' is 0.

00:05:37.910 --> 00:05:38.960 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Yeah, yeah.

00:05:38.960 --> 00:05:40.335 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So what
does that mean?

00:05:40.335 --> 00:05:41.600 align:middle line:90%
There's no commutator?

00:05:41.600 --> 00:05:44.570 align:middle line:84%
HONG LIU: Yeah, yeah,
yeah, because of the charge

00:05:44.570 --> 00:05:45.950 align:middle line:90%
conservation.

00:05:45.950 --> 00:05:48.620 align:middle line:84%
And you cannot propagate from
one particle to the other

00:05:48.620 --> 00:05:49.790 align:middle line:90%
particle.

00:05:49.790 --> 00:05:54.530 align:middle line:84%
So because phi, when
it acts on the 0,

00:05:54.530 --> 00:05:57.260 align:middle line:90%
generates, say, a particle.

00:05:57.260 --> 00:05:59.960 align:middle line:84%
But when phi acts on
the left, it actually

00:05:59.960 --> 00:06:02.690 align:middle line:90%
generates the antiparticle.

00:06:02.690 --> 00:06:06.100 align:middle line:84%
So a particle cannot become
a antiparticle, right?

00:06:06.100 --> 00:06:09.280 align:middle line:84%
So only when phi and the
phi dagger, and then it's

00:06:09.280 --> 00:06:10.810 align:middle line:90%
from just the particle.

00:06:10.810 --> 00:06:11.310 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:06:11.310 --> 00:06:16.020 align:middle line:90%


00:06:16.020 --> 00:06:16.950 align:middle line:90%
Other questions?

00:06:16.950 --> 00:06:20.280 align:middle line:90%


00:06:20.280 --> 00:06:22.200 align:middle line:90%
OK, good.

00:06:22.200 --> 00:06:25.770 align:middle line:90%
So we also discussed the--

00:06:25.770 --> 00:06:29.670 align:middle line:84%
yeah, so we wrote down
this formula for R,

00:06:29.670 --> 00:06:36.290 align:middle line:90%
A, F, say, in coordinate space.

00:06:36.290 --> 00:06:40.030 align:middle line:84%
So x prime can be written
as a Fourier transform.

00:06:40.030 --> 00:06:50.360 align:middle line:90%


00:06:50.360 --> 00:06:56.192 align:middle line:84%
I think it's k squared
plus m squared.

00:06:56.192 --> 00:06:57.905 align:middle line:90%
And let me just check the sign.

00:06:57.905 --> 00:07:00.730 align:middle line:90%


00:07:00.730 --> 00:07:03.380 align:middle line:90%
I think it's i or minus i.

00:07:03.380 --> 00:07:06.490 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, minus i.

00:07:06.490 --> 00:07:11.680 align:middle line:90%
So right, OK?

00:07:11.680 --> 00:07:18.490 align:middle line:84%
And then we mentioned that this
factor actually has a pole.

00:07:18.490 --> 00:07:22.240 align:middle line:84%
In the downstairs, these
have the form omega squared--

00:07:22.240 --> 00:07:26.140 align:middle line:84%
minus omega squared
plus omega k squared

00:07:26.140 --> 00:07:28.510 align:middle line:90%
if you write it explicitly.

00:07:28.510 --> 00:07:35.960 align:middle line:84%
And then this quantity
becomes singular at--

00:07:35.960 --> 00:07:44.985 align:middle line:84%
so singular at omega equal
to plus-minus omega k.

00:07:44.985 --> 00:07:47.305 align:middle line:90%


00:07:47.305 --> 00:07:47.805 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:07:47.805 --> 00:07:50.370 align:middle line:90%


00:07:50.370 --> 00:07:53.850 align:middle line:84%
And the singularity lies
on the integration contour

00:07:53.850 --> 00:07:57.600 align:middle line:84%
if we consider a
complex omega plane.

00:07:57.600 --> 00:08:00.990 align:middle line:84%
And so here, one of the
integral is the omega.

00:08:00.990 --> 00:08:05.710 align:middle line:84%
And then the omega go
along the real axis.

00:08:05.710 --> 00:08:07.960 align:middle line:84%
So the integration goes
along the real axis.

00:08:07.960 --> 00:08:14.150 align:middle line:84%
And here is minus omega
k, here is omega k.

00:08:14.150 --> 00:08:18.800 align:middle line:84%
So you have singularity on
the integration contour.

00:08:18.800 --> 00:08:24.890 align:middle line:84%
And then different ways of going
around the singularity then

00:08:24.890 --> 00:08:28.160 align:middle line:84%
give you different choice
of retarded and advanced

00:08:28.160 --> 00:08:30.970 align:middle line:90%
and the Feynman.

00:08:30.970 --> 00:08:34.600 align:middle line:84%
And which one to
choose based on-- which

00:08:34.600 --> 00:08:36.940 align:middle line:84%
control you should
choose, whether you

00:08:36.940 --> 00:08:41.200 align:middle line:84%
should go around, go above,
or go below the singularity.

00:08:41.200 --> 00:08:46.780 align:middle line:84%
And depends on the
prescription for each of them.

00:08:46.780 --> 00:08:52.360 align:middle line:84%
So we discussed
that for G R, which

00:08:52.360 --> 00:08:57.250 align:middle line:84%
is proportional to theta,
t minus t prime, then that

00:08:57.250 --> 00:09:01.330 align:middle line:84%
means we should-- yeah, so let
me just draw the singularity.

00:09:01.330 --> 00:09:04.220 align:middle line:90%


00:09:04.220 --> 00:09:07.690 align:middle line:84%
So that means you actually
need to change your contour

00:09:07.690 --> 00:09:14.200 align:middle line:84%
to go above the singularity, to
go above the both singularity.

00:09:14.200 --> 00:09:17.500 align:middle line:84%
OK, so that will guarantee
you to proportional

00:09:17.500 --> 00:09:22.480 align:middle line:84%
to theta minus theta prime
when you do the integral--

00:09:22.480 --> 00:09:25.300 align:middle line:84%
when you do the
integral, the omega

00:09:25.300 --> 00:09:31.570 align:middle line:84%
integral using the contours
and using the contours.

00:09:31.570 --> 00:09:38.260 align:middle line:84%
And similarly, for G A, which
is proportional to theta t

00:09:38.260 --> 00:09:41.320 align:middle line:90%
prime and t minus t prime--

00:09:41.320 --> 00:09:43.540 align:middle line:84%
in order to guarantee
that, then you

00:09:43.540 --> 00:09:50.760 align:middle line:84%
have to take your control
to be below the singularity,

00:09:50.760 --> 00:09:52.210 align:middle line:90%
be below the singularity.

00:09:52.210 --> 00:09:54.675 align:middle line:84%
So this is omega,
real omega axis.

00:09:54.675 --> 00:09:57.230 align:middle line:90%


00:09:57.230 --> 00:09:59.660 align:middle line:90%
And for the Feynman--

00:09:59.660 --> 00:10:03.610 align:middle line:84%
so the Feynman is
half and a half.

00:10:03.610 --> 00:10:06.370 align:middle line:84%
So there's a theta t minus
t prime part-- there's

00:10:06.370 --> 00:10:09.280 align:middle line:90%
a theta t prime minus t part.

00:10:09.280 --> 00:10:13.510 align:middle line:90%
OK, if you try to check that--

00:10:13.510 --> 00:10:15.670 align:middle line:84%
so we're not going
to detail it there.

00:10:15.670 --> 00:10:22.100 align:middle line:84%
Here we'll give you a
exercise for yourself.

00:10:22.100 --> 00:10:25.120 align:middle line:84%
So if you want to satisfy
that kind of condition

00:10:25.120 --> 00:10:28.870 align:middle line:84%
when t greater than t
prime gives you G plus

00:10:28.870 --> 00:10:30.820 align:middle line:84%
and when t smaller
than t prime gives you

00:10:30.820 --> 00:10:37.760 align:middle line:84%
G minus, when you do
the contour integration,

00:10:37.760 --> 00:10:39.570 align:middle line:84%
you have to do
the following way.

00:10:39.570 --> 00:10:45.240 align:middle line:84%
So for this one, you go below,
for this one you go from up.

00:10:45.240 --> 00:10:49.400 align:middle line:90%
OK, you go up.

00:10:49.400 --> 00:10:52.010 align:middle line:84%
And then there's
another way, which

00:10:52.010 --> 00:10:56.780 align:middle line:84%
is G F tilde, which is the
opposite for G F in terms

00:10:56.780 --> 00:10:57.860 align:middle line:90%
of time-ordering.

00:10:57.860 --> 00:11:00.000 align:middle line:84%
And then you will do the
opposite way over here.

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:02.150 align:middle line:84%
OK, so altogether, there
are four different ways

00:11:02.150 --> 00:11:04.460 align:middle line:84%
you can go around the
singularity that give you four

00:11:04.460 --> 00:11:08.860 align:middle line:90%
different kind of functions.

00:11:08.860 --> 00:11:10.830 align:middle line:84%
OK, they give you four
different functions.

00:11:10.830 --> 00:11:15.800 align:middle line:84%
So for those of you who are not
familiar with complex analysis

00:11:15.800 --> 00:11:21.230 align:middle line:84%
or the contour integrals, try to
refresh yourself a little bit.

00:11:21.230 --> 00:11:24.590 align:middle line:84%
Because the complex
analysis is definitely

00:11:24.590 --> 00:11:26.570 align:middle line:90%
a very, very powerful tool.

00:11:26.570 --> 00:11:29.930 align:middle line:84%
To be very familiar with
it is very important.

00:11:29.930 --> 00:11:33.130 align:middle line:90%


00:11:33.130 --> 00:11:37.000 align:middle line:84%
OK, so it's
allowing-- each time,

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:40.150 align:middle line:84%
if you have to specifier
your contour like this--

00:11:40.150 --> 00:11:43.600 align:middle line:84%
so if each time you have to
specify a contour like this,

00:11:43.600 --> 00:11:44.960 align:middle line:90%
it's not convenient.

00:11:44.960 --> 00:11:48.340 align:middle line:84%
And the physicists developed
a more convenient way

00:11:48.340 --> 00:11:50.650 align:middle line:84%
to treat all of
them in one shot.

00:11:50.650 --> 00:11:59.300 align:middle line:84%
OK, so instead of going
around the contour like this,

00:11:59.300 --> 00:12:02.680 align:middle line:84%
we just try to move
the singularity.

00:12:02.680 --> 00:12:05.480 align:middle line:84%
OK so we keep the
contour to be fixed,

00:12:05.480 --> 00:12:08.240 align:middle line:84%
but we slightly move
the singularity.

00:12:08.240 --> 00:12:11.400 align:middle line:84%
OK, for example,
for the retarded,

00:12:11.400 --> 00:12:18.500 align:middle line:84%
this is the same if I just
slightly move the singularity

00:12:18.500 --> 00:12:23.140 align:middle line:84%
by a tiny bit below
the real axis.

00:12:23.140 --> 00:12:26.380 align:middle line:84%
So if my integral
contour is like this,

00:12:26.380 --> 00:12:28.830 align:middle line:90%
then this is equivalent to that.

00:12:28.830 --> 00:12:31.620 align:middle line:84%
If this is just a tiny
part, then this one

00:12:31.620 --> 00:12:33.570 align:middle line:90%
won't affect your answer.

00:12:33.570 --> 00:12:37.300 align:middle line:84%
OK, and similarly
here, in this case,

00:12:37.300 --> 00:12:40.000 align:middle line:84%
we just move both singularity
above a little bit.

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:42.360 align:middle line:84%
And in this case, I move
one singularity above,

00:12:42.360 --> 00:12:45.090 align:middle line:84%
move one singularity
down, in which case

00:12:45.090 --> 00:12:46.620 align:middle line:84%
I don't have to
change my contour,

00:12:46.620 --> 00:12:48.990 align:middle line:84%
just slightly change
my singularity.

00:12:48.990 --> 00:12:54.390 align:middle line:84%
And this can be achieved by
so-called epsilon prescription.

00:12:54.390 --> 00:13:04.920 align:middle line:84%
So a convenient trick
is in the-- for example,

00:13:04.920 --> 00:13:10.900 align:middle line:84%
in the retarded case,
instead of this--

00:13:10.900 --> 00:13:17.370 align:middle line:84%
so we always do the integral
with the same contour.

00:13:17.370 --> 00:13:24.180 align:middle line:84%
So we don't change the
contour, but we slightly

00:13:24.180 --> 00:13:33.610 align:middle line:84%
change the integration to be
omega plus i epsilon squared

00:13:33.610 --> 00:13:37.000 align:middle line:90%
plus omega k squared.

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:40.780 align:middle line:84%
OK, so the downstairs
previously was minus omega

00:13:40.780 --> 00:13:44.400 align:middle line:90%
squared plus omega k squared.

00:13:44.400 --> 00:13:47.070 align:middle line:90%
But now, I add a tiny--

00:13:47.070 --> 00:13:49.800 align:middle line:90%
so epsilon is infinitesimal.

00:13:49.800 --> 00:13:54.027 align:middle line:90%
It's positive and infinitesimal.

00:13:54.027 --> 00:13:59.940 align:middle line:90%


00:13:59.940 --> 00:14:05.700 align:middle line:84%
So you see, by adding
such a tiny piece to here,

00:14:05.700 --> 00:14:08.960 align:middle line:84%
when you solve
this singularity--

00:14:08.960 --> 00:14:13.280 align:middle line:84%
so it's now omega plus i epsilon
equal to plus minus omega.

00:14:13.280 --> 00:14:17.150 align:middle line:84%
And then move the epsilon
to the other side,

00:14:17.150 --> 00:14:21.620 align:middle line:84%
and then the solution
becomes minus i epsilon.

00:14:21.620 --> 00:14:24.230 align:middle line:84%
And then because
epsilon is positive,

00:14:24.230 --> 00:14:27.710 align:middle line:84%
then this is slightly
in the lower half plane.

00:14:27.710 --> 00:14:34.950 align:middle line:84%
And similarly, for the advanced,
you just do a minus, OK?

00:14:34.950 --> 00:14:37.895 align:middle line:84%
And then both
singularity will move up.

00:14:37.895 --> 00:14:38.770 align:middle line:90%
And for the Feynman--

00:14:38.770 --> 00:14:43.930 align:middle line:90%


00:14:43.930 --> 00:14:47.035 align:middle line:84%
so the trick is you
can do the same thing.

00:14:47.035 --> 00:14:53.160 align:middle line:90%


00:14:53.160 --> 00:14:55.760 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:14:55.760 --> 00:15:00.320 align:middle line:90%
Sorry, I still have i k.

00:15:00.320 --> 00:15:02.870 align:middle line:90%
So this is the minus i.

00:15:02.870 --> 00:15:05.540 align:middle line:84%
So I just do k squared
plus m squared,

00:15:05.540 --> 00:15:09.800 align:middle line:84%
the whole thing minus i epsilon,
rather than change the omega,

00:15:09.800 --> 00:15:11.510 align:middle line:84%
and the whole thing
minus i epsilon.

00:15:11.510 --> 00:15:17.590 align:middle line:90%


00:15:17.590 --> 00:15:19.840 align:middle line:90%
And you can check yourself.

