OK, so so far, we discussed
the simplest free theory, just

00:28:39.220 --> 00:28:42.430 align:middle line:84%
the theory of free
scalar particles.

00:28:42.430 --> 00:28:44.620 align:middle line:90%
They don't have spin.

00:28:44.620 --> 00:28:49.480 align:middle line:84%
They have spin 0, so they don't
have any space-time component.

00:28:49.480 --> 00:28:54.040 align:middle line:84%
And they have some mass,
relativistic particles.

00:28:54.040 --> 00:28:58.030 align:middle line:84%
And later, we will talk about
electrons, which have spin 1/2,

00:28:58.030 --> 00:29:00.850 align:middle line:84%
and talk about photons,
which have spin 1.

00:29:00.850 --> 00:29:04.480 align:middle line:84%
And before talking about
them, let's talk a little bit

00:29:04.480 --> 00:29:05.620 align:middle line:90%
about interactions.

00:29:05.620 --> 00:29:08.380 align:middle line:84%
Because so far, this theory
is absolutely boring.

00:29:08.380 --> 00:29:14.470 align:middle line:84%
So even though this theory
illustrates this very important

00:29:14.470 --> 00:29:18.250 align:middle line:84%
conceptual point that somehow
when you quantize the fields

00:29:18.250 --> 00:29:19.510 align:middle line:90%
you can get particles.

00:29:19.510 --> 00:29:21.580 align:middle line:84%
OK, you can get arbitrary
number of particles.

00:29:21.580 --> 00:29:25.180 align:middle line:84%
So it's a connection between
the field and the particles.

00:29:25.180 --> 00:29:27.400 align:middle line:84%
But just in terms of
theory of particles,

00:29:27.400 --> 00:29:29.320 align:middle line:84%
this series is
absolutely boring.

00:29:29.320 --> 00:29:32.630 align:middle line:84%
There's nothing-- the
particles don't do anything.

00:29:32.630 --> 00:29:36.730 align:middle line:84%
They just go straight,
which is Newton's First Law.

00:29:36.730 --> 00:29:38.860 align:middle line:84%
They just go straight
like Newton's First Law.

00:29:38.860 --> 00:29:46.150 align:middle line:84%
And so now, let's try to add
a little bit fun to introduce

00:29:46.150 --> 00:29:47.650 align:middle line:90%
a little bit interactions.

00:29:47.650 --> 00:29:49.360 align:middle line:84%
And you will see that
when you introduce

00:29:49.360 --> 00:29:53.840 align:middle line:84%
a little bit interactions,
the story becomes much richer.

00:29:53.840 --> 00:29:57.290 align:middle line:84%
So now, let's talk
about interactions.

00:29:57.290 --> 00:30:10.100 align:middle line:90%


00:30:10.100 --> 00:30:13.870 align:middle line:84%
It turns out to
describe interactions,

00:30:13.870 --> 00:30:17.810 align:middle line:84%
a very powerful approach
is the path integral.

00:30:17.810 --> 00:30:21.340 align:middle line:84%
OK, so we will also
discuss the path integral.

00:30:21.340 --> 00:30:25.970 align:middle line:84%
So we will use the path
integral approach to describe

00:30:25.970 --> 00:30:29.180 align:middle line:90%
how to treat interactions.

00:30:29.180 --> 00:30:37.030 align:middle line:84%
And yeah, so first,
let's just say

00:30:37.030 --> 00:30:42.265 align:middle line:84%
a few words about some general
remark on interacting theories.

00:30:42.265 --> 00:30:49.450 align:middle line:90%


00:30:49.450 --> 00:30:52.805 align:middle line:84%
So previously, we
consider theories

00:30:52.805 --> 00:30:54.805 align:middle line:84%
with a Lagrangian density
of the following form.

00:30:54.805 --> 00:31:00.970 align:middle line:90%


00:31:00.970 --> 00:31:02.600 align:middle line:84%
And we find it's
a free particle.

00:31:02.600 --> 00:31:04.860 align:middle line:90%
It's a theory of free particles.

00:31:04.860 --> 00:31:07.320 align:middle line:84%
And now, we can easily
make this theory

00:31:07.320 --> 00:31:11.820 align:middle line:84%
to be of interacting
particles if we just

00:31:11.820 --> 00:31:15.000 align:middle line:90%
add some higher order powers.

00:31:15.000 --> 00:31:19.300 align:middle line:84%
So for example, one
of the simplest power

00:31:19.300 --> 00:31:22.352 align:middle line:90%
is phi to the power of 4.

00:31:22.352 --> 00:31:26.410 align:middle line:90%


00:31:26.410 --> 00:31:31.150 align:middle line:84%
So yeah, you can also add
phi to the power of 3,

00:31:31.150 --> 00:31:38.620 align:middle line:84%
but phi to the power of
3 is a little bit sick.

00:31:38.620 --> 00:31:45.860 align:middle line:84%
It's because the phi cubed
doesn't have a definite sign.

00:31:45.860 --> 00:31:50.405 align:middle line:84%
I don't have a definite
sign, and so phi cubed, say,

00:31:50.405 --> 00:31:52.460 align:middle line:84%
does not have a
well defined energy.

00:31:52.460 --> 00:31:54.440 align:middle line:84%
So your energy can go
arbitrarily negative.

00:31:54.440 --> 00:31:59.120 align:middle line:84%
And so this is the
simplest interacting theory

00:31:59.120 --> 00:32:00.620 align:middle line:90%
with a well defined energy.

00:32:00.620 --> 00:32:03.650 align:middle line:90%


00:32:03.650 --> 00:32:11.200 align:middle line:84%
So we will write this as
L0, which is the free theory

00:32:11.200 --> 00:32:14.690 align:middle line:84%
part, which we can see there,
and then the interacting part,

00:32:14.690 --> 00:32:15.190 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:32:15.190 --> 00:32:20.480 align:middle line:84%
This lambda
factorial, phi fourth.

00:32:20.480 --> 00:32:24.890 align:middle line:84%
And so this lambda, essentially
heuristic, this lambda

00:32:24.890 --> 00:32:28.170 align:middle line:84%
should characterize the
importance of this term.

00:32:28.170 --> 00:32:29.810 align:middle line:84%
So if lambda goes
to 0, of course,

00:32:29.810 --> 00:32:31.670 align:middle line:84%
then this term goes
away, and then this term

00:32:31.670 --> 00:32:32.810 align:middle line:90%
is not important.

00:32:32.810 --> 00:32:34.820 align:middle line:84%
And when lambda becomes
bigger, then this term

00:32:34.820 --> 00:32:36.480 align:middle line:90%
becomes more and more important.

00:32:36.480 --> 00:32:40.550 align:middle line:84%
And so we call the lambda
to be the coupling, which

00:32:40.550 --> 00:32:42.440 align:middle line:84%
characterizes the
importance of this term.

00:32:42.440 --> 00:32:49.740 align:middle line:90%


00:32:49.740 --> 00:32:52.980 align:middle line:84%
So now, first,
let's follow what we

00:32:52.980 --> 00:32:56.790 align:middle line:84%
were doing before for the
general quantization procedure.

00:32:56.790 --> 00:32:59.950 align:middle line:84%
We tried to write down the
classical equation of motion,

00:32:59.950 --> 00:33:01.800 align:middle line:84%
and then we
quantized-- and then we

00:33:01.800 --> 00:33:04.890 align:middle line:84%
solved the most general
classical equations,

00:33:04.890 --> 00:33:07.740 align:middle line:84%
the most general solutions
for the classical equations.

00:33:07.740 --> 00:33:11.850 align:middle line:84%
And then we promote those
solutions to operators, right?

00:33:11.850 --> 00:33:14.880 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, so let's try
to do this one.

00:33:14.880 --> 00:33:22.498 align:middle line:90%


00:33:22.498 --> 00:33:24.665 align:middle line:84%
So now, when you write down
the equation of motion--

00:33:24.665 --> 00:33:30.237 align:middle line:90%


00:33:30.237 --> 00:33:31.945 align:middle line:84%
so the equation of
motion is very simple.

00:33:31.945 --> 00:33:34.640 align:middle line:90%


00:33:34.640 --> 00:33:39.280 align:middle line:84%
You just get partial
square phi, m square phi.

00:33:39.280 --> 00:33:41.500 align:middle line:90%
So this is the free theory part.

00:33:41.500 --> 00:33:47.260 align:middle line:84%
And now, you have a
nonlinear part, the cube, OK?

00:33:47.260 --> 00:33:51.337 align:middle line:90%


00:33:51.337 --> 00:33:52.920 align:middle line:84%
So now, you have a
nonlinear equation.

00:33:52.920 --> 00:33:59.840 align:middle line:90%


00:33:59.840 --> 00:34:01.265 align:middle line:90%
So who can solve this equation?

00:34:01.265 --> 00:34:06.130 align:middle line:90%


00:34:06.130 --> 00:34:07.270 align:middle line:90%
Any volunteers?

00:34:07.270 --> 00:34:11.469 align:middle line:90%


00:34:11.469 --> 00:34:13.270 align:middle line:84%
It turns out actually
this equation,

00:34:13.270 --> 00:34:16.250 align:middle line:84%
nobody has been able
to solve it so far.

00:34:16.250 --> 00:34:18.940 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:34:18.940 --> 00:34:21.520 align:middle line:84%
So we don't know
how to solve it.

00:34:21.520 --> 00:34:24.340 align:middle line:84%
And so our previous
strategy, even though

00:34:24.340 --> 00:34:27.770 align:middle line:84%
sounds very powerful and
immediately it breaks down, OK?

00:34:27.770 --> 00:34:31.449 align:middle line:84%
Because rely on you can
actually find the solutions

00:34:31.449 --> 00:34:34.000 align:middle line:90%
to this equation of motion.

00:34:34.000 --> 00:34:38.020 align:middle line:84%
And yeah, so we don't
know how to solve this.

00:34:38.020 --> 00:34:53.159 align:middle line:90%


00:34:53.159 --> 00:34:56.420 align:middle line:84%
But heuristically,
you can imagine

00:34:56.420 --> 00:34:58.970 align:middle line:84%
that this, indeed, should
be a theory of interacting

00:34:58.970 --> 00:35:00.910 align:middle line:90%
particles.

00:35:00.910 --> 00:35:03.388 align:middle line:84%
Because previously, when
you don't have this term,

00:35:03.388 --> 00:35:04.930 align:middle line:84%
you just have a
linear equation, then

00:35:04.930 --> 00:35:06.980 align:middle line:90%
the phi is not doing anything.

00:35:06.980 --> 00:35:08.780 align:middle line:84%
OK, now, you have
a phi cubed term.

00:35:08.780 --> 00:35:11.800 align:middle line:84%
So that means that the different
phis can now doing something

00:35:11.800 --> 00:35:12.580 align:middle line:90%
together, OK?

00:35:12.580 --> 00:35:15.340 align:middle line:84%
So when different phi's
doing something together,

00:35:15.340 --> 00:35:17.350 align:middle line:84%
by definition, that's
called interactions.

00:35:17.350 --> 00:35:19.510 align:middle line:84%
OK, and that's
called interactions.

00:35:19.510 --> 00:35:22.660 align:middle line:84%
And so just heuristically,
this should already--

00:35:22.660 --> 00:35:26.405 align:middle line:84%
this should give you a theory
of interacting particles.

00:35:26.405 --> 00:35:26.905 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:35:26.905 --> 00:35:35.400 align:middle line:90%


00:35:35.400 --> 00:35:38.850 align:middle line:84%
So we will talk about how
to treat such a theory.

00:35:38.850 --> 00:35:40.800 align:middle line:84%
Since this cannot
be solved exactly,

00:35:40.800 --> 00:35:44.730 align:middle line:84%
we can only try to
solve it approximately.

00:35:44.730 --> 00:35:48.630 align:middle line:84%
So the only way we know how to
solve it approximately so far

00:35:48.630 --> 00:35:51.680 align:middle line:84%
is to imagine the
lambda is small.

00:35:51.680 --> 00:35:54.198 align:middle line:84%
And then you just expand
the lambda perturbatively.

00:35:54.198 --> 00:35:55.990 align:middle line:84%
Just treat the lambda
as a small parameter,

00:35:55.990 --> 00:35:57.700 align:middle line:90%
you just expand the lambda.

00:35:57.700 --> 00:36:01.840 align:middle line:84%
And so I will outline this
procedure in a little bit.

00:36:01.840 --> 00:36:04.820 align:middle line:84%
But before that, let me just
make some general remarks,

00:36:04.820 --> 00:36:08.675 align:middle line:84%
which apply to general
interacting theories, which

00:36:08.675 --> 00:36:10.050 align:middle line:84%
this is just one
of the examples.

00:36:10.050 --> 00:36:14.260 align:middle line:90%


00:36:14.260 --> 00:36:20.470 align:middle line:84%
So actually figuring out
interactions from experiments--

00:36:20.470 --> 00:36:26.120 align:middle line:84%
it's actually one of the main
tasks of the particle physics

00:36:26.120 --> 00:36:29.910 align:middle line:84%
and many areas of
condensed matter physics.

00:36:29.910 --> 00:36:36.500 align:middle line:84%
OK, and so for example,
we build LHC at CERN

00:36:36.500 --> 00:36:41.420 align:middle line:84%
and you collide these protons
together, billions of dollars.

00:36:41.420 --> 00:36:44.390 align:middle line:84%
The whole purpose is to
figure out the interactions

00:36:44.390 --> 00:36:46.520 align:middle line:90%
between the particles.

00:36:46.520 --> 00:36:52.790 align:middle line:84%
Between the elementary particles
and to verify them, et cetera.

00:36:52.790 --> 00:36:57.290 align:middle line:84%
And similarly, with many
condensed matter experiments.

00:36:57.290 --> 00:36:59.940 align:middle line:84%
So now, I'll ask you
a simple question.

00:36:59.940 --> 00:37:02.930 align:middle line:84%
So what's the most powerful
way, experimentally,

00:37:02.930 --> 00:37:06.920 align:middle line:84%
to probe the interactions
between particles?

00:37:06.920 --> 00:37:10.130 align:middle line:84%
What is the word to describe
that kind of experiment?

00:37:10.130 --> 00:37:14.660 align:middle line:90%


00:37:14.660 --> 00:37:16.035 align:middle line:90%
What?

00:37:16.035 --> 00:37:16.910 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Scattering.

00:37:16.910 --> 00:37:19.963 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Yeah, scattering.

00:37:19.963 --> 00:37:21.380 align:middle line:84%
So you should
already have learned

00:37:21.380 --> 00:37:23.540 align:middle line:90%
this in quantum mechanics.

00:37:23.540 --> 00:37:28.280 align:middle line:84%
So scattering is
the key thing, OK?

00:37:28.280 --> 00:37:37.980 align:middle line:84%
So that's essentially
the universal approach

00:37:37.980 --> 00:37:41.770 align:middle line:84%
we have been using for more
than 100 years, starting

00:37:41.770 --> 00:37:48.520 align:middle line:84%
from Rutherford, who first
shoot the helium atom at the--

00:37:48.520 --> 00:37:53.600 align:middle line:84%
who first shooting electrons
at the helium atom.

00:37:53.600 --> 00:37:54.240 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:37:54.240 --> 00:37:56.020 align:middle line:90%
No, no, no, no, no.

00:37:56.020 --> 00:37:58.330 align:middle line:84%
Shoot the alpha
particles at the--

00:37:58.330 --> 00:38:00.350 align:middle line:90%
alpha particles at atoms.

00:38:00.350 --> 00:38:09.600 align:middle line:84%
And so the scattering-- and
then, so you have Rutherford,

00:38:09.600 --> 00:38:15.790 align:middle line:84%
and then you have the so-called
deep inelastic scattering, DIS,

00:38:15.790 --> 00:38:18.280 align:middle line:84%
which you figured out
that the proton actually

00:38:18.280 --> 00:38:22.900 align:middle line:84%
has substructure, which leads
to the discovery of quarks.

00:38:22.900 --> 00:38:27.940 align:middle line:84%
And actually, MIT played a key
role, Friedman and Kendall,

00:38:27.940 --> 00:38:32.710 align:middle line:84%
in the DIS experiment, which
figured out the structure--

00:38:32.710 --> 00:38:37.900 align:middle line:84%
which discovered that
the quarks were--

00:38:37.900 --> 00:38:42.980 align:middle line:84%
yeah, they played
the key role in that.

00:38:42.980 --> 00:38:49.540 align:middle line:84%
So and still, many, many
interactions and the particles

00:38:49.540 --> 00:38:51.880 align:middle line:90%
were discovered this way.

00:38:51.880 --> 00:39:00.500 align:middle line:84%
And so the basic
idea of scattering--

00:39:00.500 --> 00:39:06.170 align:middle line:90%


00:39:06.170 --> 00:39:07.735 align:middle line:84%
so essentially,
it's very simple.

00:39:07.735 --> 00:39:10.280 align:middle line:90%


00:39:10.280 --> 00:39:23.220 align:middle line:84%
You just collide a
bunch of particles, OK?

00:39:23.220 --> 00:39:24.660 align:middle line:90%
And just examine the outcome.

00:39:24.660 --> 00:39:34.520 align:middle line:90%


00:39:34.520 --> 00:39:36.860 align:middle line:84%
OK, so from the outcome,
you try to deduce

00:39:36.860 --> 00:39:39.560 align:middle line:84%
what are the interactions
between those particles?

00:39:39.560 --> 00:39:42.050 align:middle line:84%
OK, so that's what
the experiment--

00:39:42.050 --> 00:39:44.570 align:middle line:90%
scattering experiment about.

00:39:44.570 --> 00:39:50.930 align:middle line:84%
OK, so from here, you deduce the
interaction, which has always

00:39:50.930 --> 00:39:53.040 align:middle line:90%
been very successful.

00:39:53.040 --> 00:39:57.350 align:middle line:84%
So in condensed matter, you have
neutron scattering, et cetera.

00:39:57.350 --> 00:40:00.110 align:middle line:84%
X-ray, you can use
X-ray and the neutrons

00:40:00.110 --> 00:40:02.135 align:middle line:90%
to shine on your samples.

00:40:02.135 --> 00:40:04.830 align:middle line:90%


00:40:04.830 --> 00:40:08.960 align:middle line:84%
And one of the most
important observables

00:40:08.960 --> 00:40:14.200 align:middle line:84%
for the scattering
experiment is what?

00:40:14.200 --> 00:40:16.943 align:middle line:84%
Again, this is a simple
question of quantum mechanics.

00:40:16.943 --> 00:40:17.735 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Momentum?

00:40:17.735 --> 00:40:18.398 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Hmm?

00:40:18.398 --> 00:40:20.240 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Momentum?

00:40:20.240 --> 00:40:21.267 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Sorry?

00:40:21.267 --> 00:40:22.338 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Momentum?

00:40:22.338 --> 00:40:23.838 align:middle line:84%
HONG LIU: No,
momentum is not that--

00:40:23.838 --> 00:40:25.152 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: And cross section.

00:40:25.152 --> 00:40:26.030 align:middle line:90%
Cross section.

00:40:26.030 --> 00:40:26.120 align:middle line:90%


00:40:26.120 --> 00:40:27.495 align:middle line:84%
HONG LIU: Cross
section is close,

00:40:27.495 --> 00:40:30.573 align:middle line:90%
but there's a more fancy word.

00:40:30.573 --> 00:40:31.448 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:40:31.448 --> 00:40:33.840 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Hmm?

00:40:33.840 --> 00:40:36.680 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Differential
cross section?

00:40:36.680 --> 00:40:40.890 align:middle line:84%
HONG LIU: That's fancier,
but not fancy enough.

00:40:40.890 --> 00:40:41.765 align:middle line:90%
It's called S-matrix.

00:40:41.765 --> 00:40:46.310 align:middle line:90%


00:40:46.310 --> 00:40:47.810 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: No, I
said S-matrix, but I

00:40:47.810 --> 00:40:48.740 align:middle line:90%
didn't say it loud enough.

00:40:48.740 --> 00:40:49.448 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Oh, OK.

00:40:49.448 --> 00:40:50.900 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, just be brave.

00:40:50.900 --> 00:40:53.090 align:middle line:90%
Be braver next time.

00:40:53.090 --> 00:40:58.440 align:middle line:90%


00:40:58.440 --> 00:41:01.520 align:middle line:90%
So one of the key elements--

00:41:01.520 --> 00:41:07.910 align:middle line:84%
yeah, so one of the key
observables for scattering

00:41:07.910 --> 00:41:09.680 align:middle line:90%
is a so-called the S-matrix.

00:41:09.680 --> 00:41:18.190 align:middle line:84%
OK, to define S-matrix,
we need a little bit

00:41:18.190 --> 00:41:23.980 align:middle line:84%
of mathematical idealization,
just as always in physics.

00:41:23.980 --> 00:41:26.160 align:middle line:84%
So the mathematical
idealization,

00:41:26.160 --> 00:41:28.980 align:middle line:84%
in order to define
S-matrix, is the following.

00:41:28.980 --> 00:41:36.770 align:middle line:90%


00:41:36.770 --> 00:41:42.780 align:middle line:84%
So at t equal to infinity,
t equal to minus infinity,

00:41:42.780 --> 00:41:47.775 align:middle line:90%
prepare initial state--

00:41:47.775 --> 00:41:56.750 align:middle line:90%


00:41:56.750 --> 00:42:06.200 align:middle line:84%
yeah, initial state may be the
initial state as localized,

00:42:06.200 --> 00:42:13.105 align:middle line:84%
say, wave packet
infinitely far apart.

00:42:13.105 --> 00:42:20.290 align:middle line:90%


00:42:20.290 --> 00:42:23.520 align:middle line:84%
So this is the mathematical
idealization part, OK?

00:42:23.520 --> 00:42:25.245 align:middle line:84%
We want them to be
infinitely far apart.

00:42:25.245 --> 00:42:32.260 align:middle line:90%


00:42:32.260 --> 00:42:34.120 align:middle line:90%
But you aim them, OK?

00:42:34.120 --> 00:42:38.050 align:middle line:84%
So you prepare them spatially
infinitely far apart,

00:42:38.050 --> 00:42:41.470 align:middle line:84%
but you aim of them-- you
prepare their initial momentum

00:42:41.470 --> 00:42:43.780 align:middle line:84%
so that they can come
together at some point.

00:42:43.780 --> 00:42:46.020 align:middle line:90%
You aim them.

00:42:46.020 --> 00:42:48.690 align:middle line:84%
And then they will come
together at some point,

00:42:48.690 --> 00:42:50.610 align:middle line:90%
and then they will scatter.

00:42:50.610 --> 00:42:53.190 align:middle line:84%
They will interact
with each other.

00:42:53.190 --> 00:42:57.930 align:middle line:84%
And then they will form
some final product,

00:42:57.930 --> 00:43:01.290 align:middle line:84%
and then the final product will
then run away from each other,

00:43:01.290 --> 00:43:01.950 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:43:01.950 --> 00:43:03.820 align:middle line:84%
They will have
velocity momentum.

00:43:03.820 --> 00:43:04.920 align:middle line:90%
They will run away.

00:43:04.920 --> 00:43:06.720 align:middle line:90%
And then you just wait.

00:43:06.720 --> 00:43:09.030 align:middle line:84%
Wait until the
products are far apart,

00:43:09.030 --> 00:43:11.160 align:middle line:90%
then you match with them.

00:43:11.160 --> 00:43:15.300 align:middle line:84%
So mathematically, this is
called t equals infinity--

00:43:15.300 --> 00:43:17.760 align:middle line:84%
yeah, of course, t equal
to plus-minus infinity

00:43:17.760 --> 00:43:20.550 align:middle line:84%
is also a mathematical
idealization.

00:43:20.550 --> 00:43:28.860 align:middle line:84%
And the final particles
are also far apart.

00:43:28.860 --> 00:43:32.250 align:middle line:90%
Again, infinitely far apart.

00:43:32.250 --> 00:43:38.520 align:middle line:84%
Because they are all
relativistic particles and they

00:43:38.520 --> 00:43:41.450 align:middle line:90%
all move.

00:43:41.450 --> 00:43:43.430 align:middle line:84%
And even with slightly
momentum difference,

00:43:43.430 --> 00:43:44.810 align:middle line:90%
eventually, they will be--

00:43:44.810 --> 00:43:47.570 align:middle line:84%
if you wait long enough
time, then they will be--

00:43:47.570 --> 00:43:51.120 align:middle line:90%


00:43:51.120 --> 00:43:53.740 align:middle line:84%
so this final path
are very important,

00:43:53.740 --> 00:44:11.050 align:middle line:84%
these two, because this means
we can neglect the interactions.

00:44:11.050 --> 00:44:17.770 align:middle line:90%


00:44:17.770 --> 00:44:22.856 align:middle line:84%
OK, as t goes to
plus-minus infinity.

00:44:22.856 --> 00:44:27.600 align:middle line:84%
OK, so with this set
up, and then t equals

00:44:27.600 --> 00:44:31.200 align:middle line:84%
plus-minus infinity,
they are very far away.

00:44:31.200 --> 00:44:32.950 align:middle line:84%
And then you can neglect
the interactions.

00:44:32.950 --> 00:44:33.630 align:middle line:90%
This is important.

00:44:33.630 --> 00:44:35.100 align:middle line:84%
Then we can identify
each particle,

00:44:35.100 --> 00:44:36.720 align:middle line:84%
because when they
are together, they

00:44:36.720 --> 00:44:39.420 align:middle line:84%
all interacting with
each other, it's

00:44:39.420 --> 00:44:41.730 align:middle line:84%
not easy to cleanly
identify each particles

00:44:41.730 --> 00:44:43.710 align:middle line:90%
and discuss their properties.

00:44:43.710 --> 00:44:47.610 align:middle line:84%
And so now, we can
neglect the interactions.

00:44:47.610 --> 00:44:56.620 align:middle line:90%


00:44:56.620 --> 00:45:15.990 align:middle line:84%
So the initial and final
states, and then a collection

00:45:15.990 --> 00:45:17.160 align:middle line:90%
of free particles.

00:45:17.160 --> 00:45:24.890 align:middle line:90%


00:45:24.890 --> 00:45:26.615 align:middle line:84%
And they can be
described by free theory.

00:45:26.615 --> 00:45:35.050 align:middle line:90%


00:45:35.050 --> 00:45:38.950 align:middle line:84%
So this is very important
because remember,

00:45:38.950 --> 00:45:41.290 align:middle line:84%
we cannot solve this kind of
interacting theory exactly.

00:45:41.290 --> 00:45:44.040 align:middle line:90%


00:45:44.040 --> 00:45:49.470 align:middle line:84%
So now, but we can reliably
almost to infinitely accuracy

00:45:49.470 --> 00:45:53.640 align:middle line:84%
if you talk about the initial
state and the final state.

00:45:53.640 --> 00:45:55.830 align:middle line:84%
And we can talk about
them as precisely

00:45:55.830 --> 00:45:59.820 align:middle line:84%
as we can, as far as we go to
t going to plus-minus infinity.

00:45:59.820 --> 00:46:00.600 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:46:00.600 --> 00:46:04.503 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So how do you know
adding a phi to the fourth term

00:46:04.503 --> 00:46:05.420 align:middle line:90%
leads to interactions?

00:46:05.420 --> 00:46:08.035 align:middle line:84%
Just because its the simplest
term that [INAUDIBLE]..

00:46:08.035 --> 00:46:09.520 align:middle line:84%
HONG LIU: Yeah,
just in principle,

00:46:09.520 --> 00:46:14.100 align:middle line:84%
any nonlinear term will
lead to interactions.

00:46:14.100 --> 00:46:16.410 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, the intuition
is that anything

00:46:16.410 --> 00:46:19.680 align:middle line:84%
beyond the linear level, you
will have different phi's

00:46:19.680 --> 00:46:20.620 align:middle line:90%
coming together.

00:46:20.620 --> 00:46:24.870 align:middle line:84%
So whether it's phi cubed,
or phi four, so higher powers

00:46:24.870 --> 00:46:26.940 align:middle line:90%
or exponentials.

00:46:26.940 --> 00:46:30.108 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, just anything
which is not linear phi's

00:46:30.108 --> 00:46:31.650 align:middle line:84%
have to do something
with each other,

00:46:31.650 --> 00:46:33.690 align:middle line:90%
and that just means interaction.

00:46:33.690 --> 00:46:34.290 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:46:34.290 --> 00:46:34.635 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:46:34.635 --> 00:46:36.427 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Why are you
doing the interaction

00:46:36.427 --> 00:46:40.950 align:middle line:84%
from the minus one half m
squared phi squared term?

00:46:40.950 --> 00:46:43.383 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Sorry, say it again.

00:46:43.383 --> 00:46:44.300 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: So we have--

00:46:44.300 --> 00:46:45.550 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Oh yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:46:45.550 --> 00:46:47.420 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, this does not
give you interactions

00:46:47.420 --> 00:46:48.530 align:middle line:90%
because this just--

00:46:48.530 --> 00:46:52.130 align:middle line:84%
remember, when you do equation
of motion, that still gives you

00:46:52.130 --> 00:46:52.880 align:middle line:90%
a linear term.

00:46:52.880 --> 00:46:53.300 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Oh, OK.

00:46:53.300 --> 00:46:54.510 align:middle line:84%
HONG LIU: Linear term
just give you a mass.

00:46:54.510 --> 00:46:54.790 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:46:54.790 --> 00:46:55.873 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Yeah yeah, yeah.

00:46:55.873 --> 00:46:56.840 align:middle line:90%
Right, right.

00:46:56.840 --> 00:46:58.610 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:46:58.610 --> 00:47:03.320 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, in the Lagrangian, the
quadratic term, a free term.

00:47:03.320 --> 00:47:05.210 align:middle line:84%
So since above
the quadratic term

00:47:05.210 --> 00:47:06.380 align:middle line:90%
gives you the interactions.

00:47:06.380 --> 00:47:07.270 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:47:07.270 --> 00:47:09.210 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:47:09.210 --> 00:47:09.710 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:47:09.710 --> 00:47:11.607 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: If I know what
the interaction potential is

00:47:11.607 --> 00:47:14.240 align:middle line:84%
to the particles, like gluon
or something like that, how

00:47:14.240 --> 00:47:15.425 align:middle line:90%
can I translate that into--

00:47:15.425 --> 00:47:16.550 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:47:16.550 --> 00:47:19.250 align:middle line:90%
Here you can not translate.

00:47:19.250 --> 00:47:22.070 align:middle line:84%
Here, I'm just giving you the
intuition that somehow when

00:47:22.070 --> 00:47:23.810 align:middle line:84%
you add such kind
of nonlinear term

00:47:23.810 --> 00:47:26.510 align:middle line:84%
that should lead to some
kind of interactions.

00:47:26.510 --> 00:47:29.720 align:middle line:84%
But to understand what
precisely kind of interactions,

00:47:29.720 --> 00:47:31.643 align:middle line:84%
you have to look at
physical observables.

00:47:31.643 --> 00:47:33.560 align:middle line:84%
So that's why we need
to look at the S-matrix.

00:47:33.560 --> 00:47:37.250 align:middle line:84%
Even for this theory,
we want to say, suppose

00:47:37.250 --> 00:47:41.000 align:middle line:84%
we have this theory,
but in real life,

00:47:41.000 --> 00:47:46.550 align:middle line:84%
how do we see in
the real experiment?

00:47:46.550 --> 00:47:49.460 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, if this theory
can be realized

00:47:49.460 --> 00:47:51.500 align:middle line:84%
in the real experiment,
what it looks like?

00:47:51.500 --> 00:47:54.410 align:middle line:84%
And the only way to see it
is through this S-matrix.

00:47:54.410 --> 00:47:55.340 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, yeah.

00:47:55.340 --> 00:48:00.020 align:middle line:84%
And so this S-matrix, and
then yeah, we can deduce back.

00:48:00.020 --> 00:48:00.520 align:middle line:90%
Good?

00:48:00.520 --> 00:48:05.470 align:middle line:90%


00:48:05.470 --> 00:48:06.510 align:middle line:90%
OK, good?

00:48:06.510 --> 00:48:09.810 align:middle line:84%
So this is important
because this makes sure

00:48:09.810 --> 00:48:14.790 align:middle line:84%
that even when we're unable
to solve the theory exactly,

00:48:14.790 --> 00:48:18.510 align:middle line:84%
we can still talk about initial
and final state exactly.

00:48:18.510 --> 00:48:19.780 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:48:19.780 --> 00:48:23.770 align:middle line:84%
At least we can define
our problem precisely.

00:48:23.770 --> 00:48:26.530 align:middle line:84%
So let's denote the
collection of initial particle

00:48:26.530 --> 00:48:31.010 align:middle line:84%
to be alpha, the momentum
of initial particles.

00:48:31.010 --> 00:48:32.540 align:middle line:84%
So essentially,
this characterizes

00:48:32.540 --> 00:48:35.780 align:middle line:90%
your initial state.

00:48:35.780 --> 00:48:38.472 align:middle line:84%
And because here we're talking
about scalar particles.

00:48:38.472 --> 00:48:40.055 align:middle line:84%
They don't have spin,
so the momentum,

00:48:40.055 --> 00:48:43.100 align:middle line:90%
they are only quantum numbers.

00:48:43.100 --> 00:48:48.020 align:middle line:84%
And say I use beta to
describe their final momentum.

00:48:48.020 --> 00:48:51.530 align:middle line:90%
I call them p 1 prime, say p n.

00:48:51.530 --> 00:48:53.780 align:middle line:84%
So the initial
number of particles

00:48:53.780 --> 00:48:57.980 align:middle line:84%
and final number of particles
don't have to be the same.

00:48:57.980 --> 00:49:01.010 align:middle line:84%
And then the scattering
process is just

00:49:01.010 --> 00:49:03.350 align:middle line:90%
to go from alpha to beta.

00:49:03.350 --> 00:49:06.200 align:middle line:84%
OK, you start a bunch of
particles at t equal to

00:49:06.200 --> 00:49:08.120 align:middle line:84%
minus infinity with
those momentum,

00:49:08.120 --> 00:49:11.780 align:middle line:84%
and then at t plus infinity,
you observe some other particles

00:49:11.780 --> 00:49:13.400 align:middle line:90%
with those momentum, OK?

00:49:13.400 --> 00:49:15.740 align:middle line:84%
And then we want to
understand the transition

00:49:15.740 --> 00:49:16.860 align:middle line:90%
amplitude between them.

00:49:16.860 --> 00:49:19.490 align:middle line:84%
So that's why the
experiment matches.

00:49:19.490 --> 00:49:21.950 align:middle line:84%
And from here, of course,
you get the cross section,

00:49:21.950 --> 00:49:23.682 align:middle line:90%
et cetera.

00:49:23.682 --> 00:49:25.265 align:middle line:84%
But this is a more
fundamental object.

00:49:25.265 --> 00:49:33.520 align:middle line:90%


00:49:33.520 --> 00:49:36.680 align:middle line:90%
So to write this precisely--

00:49:36.680 --> 00:49:48.810 align:middle line:90%


00:49:48.810 --> 00:49:50.850 align:middle line:84%
so essentially, we
are looking at, say,

00:49:50.850 --> 00:49:56.800 align:middle line:84%
in the Heisenberg picture,
this is my final state.

00:49:56.800 --> 00:50:01.830 align:middle line:84%
And I look at the evolution
from minus infinity

00:50:01.830 --> 00:50:05.200 align:middle line:84%
to plus infinity, start
from initial state alpha.

00:50:05.200 --> 00:50:10.990 align:middle line:84%
So this is the
evolution operator

00:50:10.990 --> 00:50:14.310 align:middle line:90%
of your quantum system.

00:50:14.310 --> 00:50:18.180 align:middle line:84%
And so sometimes, we also
write this as the-- so this

00:50:18.180 --> 00:50:20.190 align:middle line:90%
is in the Schrodinger picture.

00:50:20.190 --> 00:50:23.520 align:middle line:84%
And in the Heisenberg
picture, we write it as this.

00:50:23.520 --> 00:50:26.220 align:middle line:90%


00:50:26.220 --> 00:50:29.790 align:middle line:84%
So now, this means that this is
the state defined at the minus

00:50:29.790 --> 00:50:31.920 align:middle line:84%
infinity, this is
the state that's

00:50:31.920 --> 00:50:33.557 align:middle line:90%
defined as plus infinity.

00:50:33.557 --> 00:50:35.640 align:middle line:84%
So this is the notation
in the Heisenberg picture.

00:50:35.640 --> 00:50:37.860 align:middle line:84%
And this is the notation
in the Schrodinger picture.

00:50:37.860 --> 00:50:45.855 align:middle line:84%
OK, so this object
we often denote.

00:50:45.855 --> 00:50:48.420 align:middle line:90%


00:50:48.420 --> 00:50:50.070 align:middle line:90%
So you can worry--

00:50:50.070 --> 00:50:51.930 align:middle line:84%
you can run alpha
and the beta over all

00:50:51.930 --> 00:50:55.320 align:middle line:84%
possible initial states and
all possible final states.

00:50:55.320 --> 00:50:58.470 align:middle line:84%
And then that
forms a big matrix,

00:50:58.470 --> 00:51:00.930 align:middle line:84%
in fact infinite
times infinite matrix.

00:51:00.930 --> 00:51:02.790 align:middle line:90%
And so this is our S-matrix.

00:51:02.790 --> 00:51:06.160 align:middle line:90%


00:51:06.160 --> 00:51:09.850 align:middle line:84%
So essentially, all your
secret of interactions

00:51:09.850 --> 00:51:12.350 align:middle line:90%
are encoded in here.

00:51:12.350 --> 00:51:12.890 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:51:12.890 --> 00:51:15.040 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Why is it an
infinite dimensional matrix?

00:51:15.040 --> 00:51:16.540 align:middle line:84%
HONG LIU: Yeah,
because you can--

00:51:16.540 --> 00:51:21.640 align:middle line:84%
yeah, so you have a value
for any choice of alpha

00:51:21.640 --> 00:51:22.990 align:middle line:90%
and the beta, right?

00:51:22.990 --> 00:51:27.430 align:middle line:84%
And so any choice of alpha and
the beta is one matrix element.

00:51:27.430 --> 00:51:30.463 align:middle line:84%
But you have infinite possible
choice of initial momentum.

00:51:30.463 --> 00:51:32.630 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, you can have an
arbitrary number of particles,

00:51:32.630 --> 00:51:34.460 align:middle line:84%
you can have a
arbitrary momentum.

00:51:34.460 --> 00:51:37.585 align:middle line:84%
And similarly, in principle,
for the final state.

00:51:37.585 --> 00:51:38.085 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:51:38.085 --> 00:51:41.058 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: And all this
is one kind of particle?

00:51:41.058 --> 00:51:41.850 align:middle line:90%
Or how do you know?

00:51:41.850 --> 00:51:42.475 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Yeah.

00:51:42.475 --> 00:51:44.280 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, here, for this
particular problem,

00:51:44.280 --> 00:51:45.570 align:middle line:90%
it's one kind of particle.

00:51:45.570 --> 00:51:47.072 align:middle line:84%
But this definition
is very general.

00:51:47.072 --> 00:51:48.280 align:middle line:90%
This is a very good question.

00:51:48.280 --> 00:51:51.550 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't matter whether you
have one kind of particle,

00:51:51.550 --> 00:51:54.780 align:middle line:84%
two kinds of particle, even an
infinite number of particles.

00:51:54.780 --> 00:51:55.620 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:51:55.620 --> 00:51:57.520 align:middle line:84%
An infinite species
of particles.

00:51:57.520 --> 00:52:00.540 align:middle line:84%
So here, even for one
kind the particle,

00:52:00.540 --> 00:52:02.970 align:middle line:84%
I have infinite possible
choices because I

00:52:02.970 --> 00:52:05.580 align:middle line:84%
have infinite possible choice
of all those momentums.

00:52:05.580 --> 00:52:09.240 align:middle line:84%
I can choose k equal to
1, 2, 3, to infinity.

00:52:09.240 --> 00:52:11.430 align:middle line:84%
And also, the value of
those k can all change.

00:52:11.430 --> 00:52:13.010 align:middle line:90%
P can change.

00:52:13.010 --> 00:52:13.670 align:middle line:90%
So yeah.

00:52:13.670 --> 00:52:15.587 align:middle line:84%
So this is the infinite
times infinite matrix.

00:52:15.587 --> 00:52:20.440 align:middle line:90%


00:52:20.440 --> 00:52:25.212 align:middle line:90%
OK, so essentially, this S--

00:52:25.212 --> 00:52:26.920 align:middle line:84%
this is essentially
just a matrix element

00:52:26.920 --> 00:52:29.598 align:middle line:90%
of this evolution operator.

00:52:29.598 --> 00:52:31.390 align:middle line:84%
OK, essentially, this
is the matrix element

00:52:31.390 --> 00:52:32.473 align:middle line:90%
of the evolution operator.

00:52:32.473 --> 00:52:36.010 align:middle line:84%
You can see it from here
explicitly from minus infinity

00:52:36.010 --> 00:52:36.910 align:middle line:90%
to plus infinity.

00:52:36.910 --> 00:52:42.190 align:middle line:90%
OK, good?

00:52:42.190 --> 00:52:45.450 align:middle line:90%


00:52:45.450 --> 00:52:48.770 align:middle line:84%
So it's convenient--
so let me just

00:52:48.770 --> 00:52:55.020 align:middle line:84%
say a few things
about the S-matrix.

00:52:55.020 --> 00:52:58.290 align:middle line:84%
So it's convenient-- so when
the interaction is weak--

00:52:58.290 --> 00:53:06.940 align:middle line:90%


00:53:06.940 --> 00:53:10.708 align:middle line:84%
so when the interaction
is weak, you can imagine,

00:53:10.708 --> 00:53:12.500 align:middle line:84%
most of the time, the
particles, they don't

00:53:12.500 --> 00:53:15.740 align:middle line:90%
interact with each other, OK?

00:53:15.740 --> 00:53:18.590 align:middle line:84%
So when you do the
scattering, you

00:53:18.590 --> 00:53:20.400 align:middle line:84%
put a bunch of
particles scattering--

00:53:20.400 --> 00:53:22.160 align:middle line:84%
if the interaction
is very weak, then

00:53:22.160 --> 00:53:26.660 align:middle line:84%
they don't actually
interact very much.

00:53:26.660 --> 00:53:32.590 align:middle line:84%
So we expect-- so when
the S equals to identity,

00:53:32.590 --> 00:53:35.340 align:middle line:84%
then that means there's
no interaction at all.

00:53:35.340 --> 00:53:39.100 align:middle line:84%
OK, for free theory, it
will be just the identity.

00:53:39.100 --> 00:53:41.350 align:middle line:84%
So now, if you're seeing
that the interaction is weak,

00:53:41.350 --> 00:53:43.720 align:middle line:84%
and then it's convenient,
we write the S-matrix

00:53:43.720 --> 00:53:48.940 align:middle line:84%
in the following form, i T, and
this includes the interaction

00:53:48.940 --> 00:53:49.540 align:middle line:90%
part.

00:53:49.540 --> 00:53:54.170 align:middle line:90%
OK, captures interacting effect.

00:53:54.170 --> 00:53:59.475 align:middle line:90%


00:53:59.475 --> 00:53:59.975 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:53:59.975 --> 00:54:06.790 align:middle line:90%


00:54:06.790 --> 00:54:08.270 align:middle line:90%
Good?

00:54:08.270 --> 00:54:13.860 align:middle line:84%
And by definition-- yeah,
any questions on this?

00:54:13.860 --> 00:54:14.370 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:54:14.370 --> 00:54:17.194 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So I was interpreting
the elements of the S-matrix

00:54:17.194 --> 00:54:19.294 align:middle line:84%
as sort of the
probability to end up

